 to discuss these issues, and look at changes in the ways citizens view democracy, governments, and legislation. As part of the Trends Series to examine Canadian public policy from the point of view of academia, this book explores important changes in modern society and will be an essential resource for future Canadian policy development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical participationzCanada. 0aRepresentative government and representationzCanada. 0aSocial valueszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aDocherty, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanji, Mebs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadeau, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevitte, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevitte, Neil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoese, Neal J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoung, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268300640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442683006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442683006.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK